Github Actions:

# 

<span key="6f61d05e3ead426b9b60cf7f90348d00"><span offset-key="6f61d05e3ead426b9b60cf7f90348d00:0">Github Actions</span></span>

## 

<span key="3255d28dcdc645b8afdaf38d9ab89386"><span offset-key="3255d28dcdc645b8afdaf38d9ab89386:0">Objective</span></span>

<span key="91f0b50cfb494afe812781bebdd9293e"><span offset-key="91f0b50cfb494afe812781bebdd9293e:0">Provide an introduction to github actions, continuous integrations, and continuous delivery</span></span>

## 

<span key="95deb8066a4544deb766f419e9e8fe87"><span offset-key="95deb8066a4544deb766f419e9e8fe87:0">Technologies</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="404d1f6769314c9b8bed09bbc6a313de"><span offset-key="404d1f6769314c9b8bed09bbc6a313de:0">Github Actions</span></span>

### 

<span key="679313a57df7476ea53565dbb1155f07"><span offset-key="679313a57df7476ea53565dbb1155f07:0">What are Github Actions</span></span>

<span key="8b1fdccdfe6343a7bc9dbfc3ff5e8c85"><span offset-key="8b1fdccdfe6343a7bc9dbfc3ff5e8c85:0">Github actions provide developers the ability to automate routine and necessary tasks. This will allow you to spend more time on this things you love (like code üë®‚Äçüíª).</span></span>

<span key="f94f291c6bd0410e8a179718652cf956"><span offset-key="f94f291c6bd0410e8a179718652cf956:0">When a user interacts with a Github repository an event triggers (eg. push request, pull request, merge requests). Developers can use these events to start an automated workflow ‚Äî A git hub container with a set of instructions or actions. Rather than write actions from scratch, the most common actions have been provided by the Github community each on a repository capable of being forked and modified.</span></span>

<span key="e5af681c08574916bcd9b4adb249d863"><span offset-key="e5af681c08574916bcd9b4adb249d863:0">Common use cases for GitHub Actions include Continuous Integration, and Continuous Deployment</span></span>

### 

<span key="b8cced041bd74704b284e58413c0ef43"><span offset-key="b8cced041bd74704b284e58413c0ef43:0">Setting up GitHub Actions</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="2336e67172494d6a8cf468762b655ac0"><span offset-key="2336e67172494d6a8cf468762b655ac0:0">For every repository on GitHub there is an actions tab, which provides a log of every action performed on the server</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4b0d19ac71ae495a93cd69d94dfd0aea"><span offset-key="4b0d19ac71ae495a93cd69d94dfd0aea:0">In your repo .githib folder you will need to have a workflows folder, with each workflow as a .yml file. GitHub will automatically recognize all .yml files in this folder as workflows.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="7313c360875d4df881008d73c877832c"><span offset-key="7313c360875d4df881008d73c877832c:0">For each workflow you will want to make a separate .yml folder </span></span><span slate-void="true" key="d1d4b9c620e546e49f1cde0c336dacbf"></span>

    <span key="b89a5e643e70413bbf0389cdc6734e29"><span offset-key="b89a5e643e70413bbf0389cdc6734e29:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">‚Äã</span></span></span>

### 

<span key="f203593ae3f649c8af3a84e8718f53dc"><span offset-key="f203593ae3f649c8af3a84e8718f53dc:0">Parts of a YML File</span></span>

<span key="bb3d4f50eadb4d79b9c2123cb254fd10"><span offset-key="bb3d4f50eadb4d79b9c2123cb254fd10:0">A YML file, similar to a python script operates with indentation. Spacing determines what is nested beneath each operator.</span></span>

<span key="08012fbd8b1f48789b73bf23df930a1d"><span offset-key="08012fbd8b1f48789b73bf23df930a1d:0">Example .YML folder</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="3bf933ebe56c4a2898d8565d4c31b2dd"><span offset-key="3bf933ebe56c4a2898d8565d4c31b2dd:0">On line 1, "name:" declares the name of the workflow</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="53370d3c5e654179be9514071e34c98e"><span offset-key="53370d3c5e654179be9514071e34c98e:0">On line 2, "on:" declares the events that trigger the workflow. In this example, the workflow will be triggered whenever the user makes a pull request, or pushes to the master branch</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="26775b1e53c74bdb98402a7285f3e368"><span offset-key="26775b1e53c74bdb98402a7285f3e368:0">On line 8, "jobs:" declares the actions that will occur when a triggering event occurs. The next level of indent declares the name.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="af974891954d4831b9ec4529292b0cc7"><span offset-key="af974891954d4831b9ec4529292b0cc7:0">On line 11, "runs-on:" determines what operating system you wish to run on the GitHub virtual machine (Where the actions are being performed on GitHub)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="c74cec33ca124d9c9d7e0097198b961b"><span offset-key="c74cec33ca124d9c9d7e0097198b961b:0">On line 13, "env:" establishes environmental configuration, often for establishing secrets, such as this case. PERSONAL\_TOKEN is the name we gave our secret on the repository. A new secret can be added by going to settings on your repository-> Secrets -> New Secret(see image below).</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="6dcac3a9b15c4396a7e3d297f123fa40"><span offset-key="6dcac3a9b15c4396a7e3d297f123fa40:0">On line 14, "steps:" list the set of instructions for the action.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="57692e0716de49b5a715ac188a04eb4b"><span offset-key="57692e0716de49b5a715ac188a04eb4b:0">In this example, first two actions (lines 15 and 18) are official actions that get our source code into the virtual machine (actions/<a href="../../../../../cdn-cgi/l/email-protection.html" class="__cf_email__">[email¬†protected]</a>) and setting up node (actions/<a href="../../../../../cdn-cgi/l/email-protection.html" class="__cf_email__">[email¬†protected]</a>). You will see these pretty often and most of your workflows will probably start with these.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="ccd1e4dc0c734aa983f79118349a02df"><span offset-key="ccd1e4dc0c734aa983f79118349a02df:0">Lines 19-22, install and a linter that test Markdown</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0faa0ef45b7b4772806d3bc7b25543a7"><span offset-key="0faa0ef45b7b4772806d3bc7b25543a7:0">The rest of the actions you see are custom scripts, or setting up the environment for this project and will vary from project to project. This is a simple continuos deployment example.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="bbcbdbfe32464b719cdf7e4127929302"><span offset-key="bbcbdbfe32464b719cdf7e4127929302:0">In this example, we are installing markdownlint to test the formatting of our markdown files, we are setting up a python environment, and we then run a python program called mkdocs that builds simple website from our markdown files. If it was pushed, we then we set up continuous deployment to deploy to github pages.</span></span>

### 

<span key="993d2cbfc65749148445e6268c4156cb"><span offset-key="993d2cbfc65749148445e6268c4156cb:0">Continuous Deployment</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="913c6a7c55764c7d90fbba3d17fc16b8"><span offset-key="913c6a7c55764c7d90fbba3d17fc16b8:0">The example above was an example of using GitHub Actions for continuous deployment.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="18cddd6f1d394dc3a06bfdc944e59fef"><span offset-key="18cddd6f1d394dc3a06bfdc944e59fef:0">The purpose of continuous deployment is to push the code that we have written to our customers or a third party quickly and automatically. This allows features and bug fixes to be applied multiple times a day, once it passes our Quality Assurance checks.</span></span>

### 

<span key="2116ad3ae6b645adbf9ed6843b8389d1"><span offset-key="2116ad3ae6b645adbf9ed6843b8389d1:0">Example: Continuous Integration</span></span>

<span key="ed9fc95985dd458596fa8ea002fbcbb0"><span offset-key="ed9fc95985dd458596fa8ea002fbcbb0:0">The purpose of continuous integration is to streamline the process to merge developer's code multiple times per day.</span></span>

<span key="268d96829979433fbf89dbf21b7259f7"><span offset-key="268d96829979433fbf89dbf21b7259f7:0">For continuous integration to work, every time a pull request is made, GitHub will run test script(s). It also will let you know how they went. If any tests fail or the build fails, the actions will have a red x letting you know that have a little more work to do. If all the tests pass you will get a little green checkmark ‚úî and the reviewers will trust your changes. Yay! üòÄ</span></span>

<span key="5673adfbfa1b4c7690d7adf2fd6a2e9e"><span offset-key="5673adfbfa1b4c7690d7adf2fd6a2e9e:0">The code here uses the community action paanbati/codeclimate-action to integrate with the Lambda Labs code climate.</span></span>
